            <div class="flex justify-between items-center">
              <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Human Age Equivalent</span>
              <span class="text-xl font-bold text-green-600 dark:text-green-400" data-dog-age-calculator-target="humanAge">— years</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <button data-action="click->dog-age-calculator#copy" class="mt-6 w-full px-4 py-2.5 bg-gradient-to-r from-green-600 to-emerald-600 hover:from-green-700 hover:to-emerald-700 text-white rounded-xl shadow-sm shadow-green-500/20 hover:shadow-md hover:shadow-green-500/25 transition-all duration-200 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-green-500 focus:ring-offset-2 text-sm font-medium">Copy Result</button>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <%# Ad: in_results %>
    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <%# SEO Article Content %>
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Dog Age Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our free dog age calculator converts your dog's chronological age into a human-years equivalent that accounts for breed size. Enter your dog's age in years (you can use half-years, such as 1.5 for eighteen months) and select the size category that best matches your dog — small (under 10 kg), medium (10-25 kg), or large (over 25 kg). The calculator instantly displays the equivalent human age. Results update in real time as you change either input, with no buttons to press and no page reloads required.
      </p>
      <p>
        Understanding your dog's age in human terms helps you provide appropriate care at each life stage. A 7-year-old large breed dog is roughly equivalent to a 62-year-old human and may benefit from senior health screenings, while a 7-year-old small breed is closer to 44 human years and likely still in its prime. This perspective can guide decisions about diet, exercise, veterinary check-ups, and expectations for energy and behavior.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Beyond the 7-Year Myth</h2>
      <p>
        The popular belief that one dog year equals seven human years is a dramatic oversimplification that has persisted for decades despite being inaccurate. Dogs mature far more quickly in their early years — most dogs reach sexual maturity by 6-12 months and are fully grown by 1-2 years. A one-year-old dog is physiologically closer to a 15-year-old teenager than a 7-year-old child. By age 2, most dogs are roughly equivalent to a 24-year-old human adult, having completed their major developmental milestones.
      </p>

      <h3>How Size Affects Aging</h3>
      <p>
        After the initial rapid maturation period, the rate at which dogs age diverges significantly based on size. <strong>Small dogs</strong> (under 10 kg) age the most slowly, adding approximately 4 human years for each calendar year after age 2. <strong>Medium dogs</strong> (10-25 kg) add about 5 human years per calendar year. <strong>Large dogs</strong> (over 25 kg) age the fastest, adding roughly 6 human years per calendar year. This is why a 10-year-old Chihuahua (56 human years) may still be sprightly, while a 10-year-old Great Dane (66 human years) is in the twilight of its expected lifespan. The biological reasons for this size-longevity relationship are still being researched, but likely involve faster cellular aging and higher metabolic demands in larger bodies.
      </p>

      <h3>Life Stage Guidelines for Dog Owners</h3>
      <p>
        Puppies (0-1 year) need vaccinations, socialization, and high-calorie puppy food. Young adults (1-3 years) are at peak energy and benefit from regular exercise and training. Mature adults (3-7 years for large breeds, 3-10 years for small breeds) should maintain a consistent routine with annual veterinary visits. Senior dogs benefit from biannual check-ups, joint supplements if recommended by a vet, softer food or dental care, and gentler exercise routines. Giant breeds like Great Danes may enter their senior phase as early as age 5-6, while toy breeds may not show senior signs until age 12 or later.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Is the 7-year rule for dog ages accurate?</h3>
      <p>
        The old rule that 1 dog year equals 7 human years is a significant oversimplification. Dogs mature much faster in their first two years — a 1-year-old dog is roughly equivalent to a 15-year-old human, and a 2-year-old dog is about 24 in human years. After age 2, the rate of aging depends heavily on the dog's size, with larger breeds aging faster than smaller ones.
      </p>

      <h3>Why do small dogs live longer than large dogs?</h3>
      <p>
        Large dogs age more rapidly than small dogs, likely because their bodies work harder to maintain their larger size, leading to faster cellular deterioration. A Great Dane's lifespan averages 7-10 years, while a Chihuahua can live 14-18 years. Large breed puppies also grow much faster, which may contribute to earlier onset of age-related diseases. The exact biological mechanisms are still being studied.
      </p>

      <h3>How does breed size affect a dog's age in human years?</h3>
      <p>
        After the first two years, small dogs (under 10 kg) add about 4 human years for each calendar year. Medium dogs (10-25 kg) add about 5 human years per calendar year. Large dogs (over 25 kg) add about 6 human years per calendar year. This means a 10-year-old small dog is roughly 56 in human years, while a 10-year-old large dog is about 66.
      </p>

      <h3>At what age is a dog considered senior?</h3>
      <p>
        The age at which a dog is considered senior depends on size. Small dogs are generally classified as senior around age 10-12, medium dogs around age 8-10, and large or giant breeds around age 6-8. Senior dogs may need more frequent veterinary check-ups, dietary adjustments, and modified exercise routines to maintain their quality of life.
      </p>

      <h3>How can I help my dog age healthily?</h3>
      <p>
        To support healthy aging, provide regular veterinary check-ups (at least annually, biannually for seniors), a balanced diet appropriate for your dog's life stage and size, consistent moderate exercise, dental care, and mental stimulation. Watch for signs of common age-related conditions such as arthritis, vision loss, cognitive decline, and weight changes. Early detection and management make a significant difference in quality of life.
      </p>
    </article>

